To understand the emission behavior of the untreated, as well as the CDs treated with three different methods, we excited the CDs using wavelengths from 420 nm to 490 nm. As shown in Fig. 2
                        a, CDs-1 shows the EIE feature, i.e., the emission peak is not affected by the change in excitation wavelength. Fig. 2b shows the CDs-2 exhibits the same EIE characteristics as CDs-1. Meanwhile, CDs-2 (42%) possesses a higher quantum yield than CDs-1 (36%) (Table .1
                        ). CDs formed with the assistance of strong acids were named as CPDs by Liu [44] et al. For CPDs, cross-linked enhanced emission (CEE) is the main contribution to the photoluminescence (PL) of CPDs [45,46]. The presence of sulfuric acid promotes carbonization, which in turn promotes the formation of rigid structures, resulting in CEE effects that enhance emission and increase quantum yields [47,48]. Most importantly, the fluorescence emission of CPDs formed with the assistance of strong acids is independent of the excitation wavelength [49]. The fluorescence intensity and quantum yields of CDs-3 (61%) and CDs-4 (68%) were similarly increased. For the emission behavior of CDs-3 and CDs-4, both CDs exhibited excitation-dependent emission (EDE), with a red-shift in the emission peak of CDs-3 and a blue-shift in the emission peak of CDs-4 (Fig. 2c∼d). The doping of sulfur atoms in CDs-3 changes the electron energy level, which leads to stronger photoluminescence and shifts in emission wavelengths [50]. And the PL performance of CDs-4 was enhanced after PEG passivation treatment, which is consistent with the previous reported work [51,52]. By tuning the surface state structure of CDs through passivation, it is possible to change the electronic energy level and modulate the optical behavior [52,53].
